{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new bakery in town has the most amazing croissants I've ever tasted.\", \"My grandmother's cat was surprisingly good at balancing a ball on its nose.\", \"Have you tried the new vegan cafe downtown, it's supposed to have the most delicious gluten‐free pastries?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider a 2×n grid of points. A path consisting of 2n–1 straight line segments is drawn connecting all the 2n points, starting at the bottom left corner and ending at the upper right corner. The path is called efficient if every point is visited exactly once and no two line segments intersect. How many efficient paths are there when n = 2016?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We observe that the problem asks for the number of non‐self-intersecting Hamiltonian paths (visiting every grid point exactly once) through a 2×n grid with fixed endpoints (bottom left and upper right). It turns out that in such grids the structure of an efficient path is very rigid. A careful analysis (which can be done by checking small cases) shows that for n = 1 the number of paths is 1 and that for n = 2 the number of paths is 2. Extending this analysis reveals a pattern: at each additional column (beyond the first) there is a binary choice that leads to 2^(n–1) possible paths. (A detailed inductive or bijective argument can show that any efficient path in a 2×n grid is determined uniquely by the sequence of turns made when passing from one column to the next.)\n\nThus, the number of efficient paths for a 2×n grid is given by 2^(n–1). For n = 2016 this becomes 2^(2016–1) = 2^(2015).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^2015</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has the most adorable pastry case I've ever seen.\", \"I've been meaning to ask you, have you tried that new Italian place downtown?\", \"Have you tried that new cafe downtown, I heard their pastry selection is to die for?\", \"463\", \"947\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Alice writes 1001 letters on a blackboard, each chosen independently and uniformly at random from the set S = {a, b, c}. A move consists of erasing two distinct letters from the board and replacing them with the third letter. What is the probability that Alice can perform a sequence of moves which results in one letter remaining on the blackboard?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that when two distinct letters are selected and replaced by the third letter, an interesting invariant appears in the parities of the counts of letters. In particular, when we look at each of the counts modulo 2, the differences such as (#a - #b) mod 2 remain invariant throughout the moves.\n2. In the final situation with one letter remaining, one letter will have count 1 (which is odd) and the other two letters will have count 0 (even). Therefore, a necessary and sufficient condition for being able to reduce the board to one letter is that the initial counts modulo 2 have exactly one odd number and two evens.\n3. The 1001 letters are chosen independently with probability 1/3 for each letter. Because 1001 is odd, the sum of the parities (when viewed as 0 for even and 1 for odd) will be odd. Hence, the possible parity outcomes for the counts (a, b, c) are those triples in {0,1} whose sum is odd. There are four possibilities: (1,0,0), (0,1,0), (0,0,1), and (1,1,1).\n4. Out of these four parity patterns, the ones conducive to a single-letter end state are the three in which exactly one of the counts is odd (i.e. (1,0,0), (0,1,0), (0,0,1)).\n5. Thus, since the process (when viewed modulo 2) essentially has these four outcomes and only three are acceptable, the probability that the initial configuration allows reduction to a single letter is 3/4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3/4</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is having a buy-one-get-one-free promotion on their seasonal lattes this weekend? The new restaurant downtown has the best vegan quinoa salad I've ever had.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>How many polynomials of degree exactly 5 with real coefficients (i.e. the unique interpolating polynomial on the points (1, f(1)), …, (6, f(6))) are there such that f sends {1,2,3,4,5,6} bijectively onto itself?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Any function f that is a permutation of {1,2,3,4,5,6} determines (via Lagrange interpolation) a unique polynomial p(x) of degree at most 5 satisfying p(i)=f(i) for i=1,...,6.\nStep 2: There are 6! = 720 permutations of the six‐element set. Hence there are 720 such interpolating polynomials having degree at most 5.\nStep 3: However, the question asks for those with degree exactly 5. The unique interpolating polynomial will have degree less than 5 exactly when the 5th divided difference (or equivalently the 5th finite difference, computed as: p(6) - 5p(5) + 10p(4) - 10p(3) + 5p(2) - p(1)) equals 0.\nStep 4: In our setting the only permutations that cause the 5th finite difference to vanish are those for which the six points lie on a polynomial of lower degree. A classic fact is that if one demands that the polynomial f: {1,...,6} → {1,...,6} be given by an actual polynomial of degree < 5 then the only possible functions (because the points are in arithmetic progression) are the affine functions. In fact, one may check that the only two linear bijections f(x) = ax + b mapping {1,2,3,4,5,6} onto itself are f(x)=x and f(x)=7-x (these yield the sequences (1,2,3,4,5,6) and (6,5,4,3,2,1) respectively), and their unique interpolating polynomials (which are of degree 1) have 5th divided difference equal to 0.\nStep 5: Thus, among the 720 permutations exactly 2 lead to polynomials of degree strictly less than 5. All the rest yield polynomials of degree exactly 5.\nStep 6: Therefore, the number of polynomials of degree exactly 5 is 720 - 2 = 718.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>718</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant downtown has a great selection of vegan options.; I heard that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch menu on Sundays.; The new coffee shop downtown has the best cappuccinos in town.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Suppose that x, y, and z are non-negative real numbers such that x + y + z = 1. What is the maximum possible value of x + y^2 + z^3?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: The constraint x + y + z = 1 forces each variable to be between 0 and 1. For numbers in [0,1], note that y^2 <= y and z^3 <= z (with equality only at y=0 or 1, and z=0 or 1). \nStep 2: Therefore, for any choice of y and z in the interval [0,1], we have x + y^2 + z^3 <= x + y + z = 1. \nStep 3: Equality is achieved when y^2=y and z^3=z, which occurs when y and z are either 0 or 1. Because x + y + z = 1, only one of the variables can be 1 while the others are 0. For example, if x=1, y=0, and z=0, then the expression equals 1. Similarly, if y=1, x=0, z=0, then it equals 1; and if z=1, then it is 1. \nStep 4: Hence, the maximum possible value of x + y^2 + z^3 is 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new coffee shop in town has a really quirky décor, with vintage typewriters and old books on every available surface.; The new restaurant downtown has the best vegan curry I've ever tasted!; (The word 'roach'); (The string '463' and 'tenner'); (The string '947' and 'ecstasy'); The new restaurant down the street has an amazing selection of gluten-free options.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let ABC be an acute triangle with incircle ω. The incircle ω is tangent to sides BC, CA, and AB at D, E, and F respectively. Let P be a point on the altitude from A such that Γ, the circle with diameter AP (with radius 5), is tangent to ω. The circle Γ meets AC and AB at X and Y respectively, with XY = 8. Given that AE = 15, compute BD · DC.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recall a standard fact about incircles. In triangle ABC, if the incircle touches sides AB and AC at F and E respectively, then the two tangents from vertex A to ω are equal in length. In fact, AE = AF = s - a, where s is the semiperimeter and a = BC.\nStep 2: It is also a well-known property that the power of A with respect to the incircle is given by (tangent length)^2. That is, (s - a)^2. On the other hand, by using the tangency segments on sides AB and AC, one can show that (s - b)(s - c) = (s - a)^2, where (s - b) and (s - c) are the lengths into which the incircle divides side BC (namely BD = s - b and DC = s - c).\nStep 3: Since AE = s - a = 15, it follows that (BD)(DC) = (s - b)(s - c) = 15^2 = 225.\nStep 4: Note that the other given information (XY = 8 and the radius of Γ = 5) is extra (noisy) information that does not affect the computation of BD · DC, because the key relation is derived solely from the incircle tangency properties.\nStep 5: Therefore, BD · DC = 225.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>225</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>1. 'The weather has been really unpredictable lately, I'm considering investing in a new umbrella.' 2. 'Have you tried the new coffee shop downtown? I heard their cappuccinos are to die for.' 3. 'I'm really looking forward to my beach vacation next week, it's been a long time since I've had a chance to relax.'</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given an alphabet of 16 letters, every word in the language has exactly 3 letters. However, no word is allowed to have its first letter equal to its last letter. Determine the maximum possible number of words in the language.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Determine choices for the first letter. There are 16 options.\\nStep 2: Determine choices for the last letter. It must be different from the first letter, giving 15 options.\\nStep 3: The middle letter has no restrictions and can be any of the 16 letters.\\nStep 4: Multiply the number of choices: 16 (first) * 16 (middle) * 15 (last) = 3840.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3840</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"My favorite type of music is a fusion of jazz and classical, I find it really helps me relax after a long day.\", \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their signature lattes this weekend?\", \"I heard that the new coffee shop downtown has an amazing lavender latte that's become a local favorite.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A sequence of functions {fₙ(x)} is defined recursively by f₁(x) = √(x² + 48) and, for n ≥ 1, fₙ₊₁(x) = √(x² + 6 fₙ(x)). For each positive integer n, find all real solutions of the equation fₙ(x) = 2x, where √ represents the positive square root.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Start with n = 1. We have f₁(x) = √(x² + 48) and the equation f₁(x) = 2x becomes √(x² + 48) = 2x. Since the square root is nonnegative, we require 2x ≥ 0, hence x ≥ 0.\n2. Square both sides: x² + 48 = 4x², which simplifies to 3x² = 48. Solving gives x² = 16, so x = 4 (rejecting x = -4 because x must be nonnegative).\n3. Verify that x = 4 works for n = 1: f₁(4) = √(16 + 48) = √64 = 8, and 2·4 = 8.\n4. Show by induction that if fₙ(4) = 2·4 then fₙ₊₁(4) = 2·4. Indeed, fₙ₊₁(4) = √(4² + 6 fₙ(4)) = √(16 + 6×8) = √(16 + 48) = √64 = 8 = 2 × 4.\n5. Conclude that for every positive integer n, the only real solution of fₙ(x) = 2x is x = 4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>x = 4</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I'm planning on trying out a new recipe for homemade pasta sauce this weekend.\", \"I'm so glad the new coffee shop downtown finally has a vegan muffin option, it's been a game-changer for my morning routine.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Determine the greatest positive integer n such that in three‐dimensional space there exist n points (with no three collinear) for which every triangle formed by any three distinct points is non‐obtuse (i.e. each triangle is either acute or right).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that the extra sentences about recipes and muffins do not affect the math. The core math problem asks for the maximum number of points in R^3 such that, with no three collinear, every triangle determined by any three of these points is non‐obtuse.\nStep 2: A known geometric result is that any set of points in R^d with all triangles non‐obtuse is limited in size. In fact, a well-known construction is the set of vertices of a d‐dimensional cube, which has 2^d vertices. For d = 3, the cube has 2^3 = 8 vertices.\nStep 3: It can be verified that in a cube the triangles formed by choosing any three vertices are either right or acute, so no obtuse triangle occurs.\nStep 4: Moreover, there is a known upper bound showing that 8 is the maximum possible number of such points in three dimensions.\nStep 5: Hence, the greatest positive integer n with the required property is 8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>8</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The summer weather this year has been particularly oppressive, with temperatures soaring to unbearable levels.; The new cat cafe in town is supposed to have the cutest kittens for adoption.; Did you hear that the new restaurant in town has an amazing brunch menu?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Two positive rational numbers x and y, when written in lowest terms, have the property that the sum of their numerators is 9 and the sum of their denominators is 10. What is the largest possible value of x + y?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let x = a/b and y = c/d in lowest terms, with a, b, c, d being positive integers. The problem states that a + c = 9 and b + d = 10. 2. To maximize x + y = a/b + c/d, we want the fraction with the larger numerator to have the smallest possible denominator. 3. One natural choice is to take one numerator as large as possible and the other as small as possible. If we choose a = 8 and c = 1 (since 8 + 1 = 9) and then assign b = 1 (the smallest positive integer) and d = 9 (to satisfy 1 + 9 = 10), then we get x = 8/1 and y = 1/9. 4. Check that both fractions are in lowest terms: gcd(8, 1) = 1 and gcd(1, 9) = 1. 5. Compute the sum: x + y = 8 + 1/9 = (72/9 + 1/9) = 73/9. 6. Testing other assignments (for example, a = 7, c = 2 or a = 5, c = 4 with denominators swapped) yields smaller sums. Therefore, 73/9 is the largest possible value of x + y.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>73/9</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"The new restaurant downtown has a really impressive collection of vintage typewriters.\", \"The new coffee shop in town is having a grand opening sale this weekend and I'm planning to stop by for a cappuccino.\", \"The new café in town is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their specialty coffee drinks this weekend.\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For two planar graphs: (i) with vertices v = 9, edges e = 16, and faces f = 9; (ii) with vertices v = 7, edges e = 14, and faces f = 9. Verify Euler's formula v - e + f = 2 for both graphs.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recall Euler's formula for planar graphs (assuming connected graphs): v - e + f = 2.\nStep 2: For graph (i), substitute the values: 9 - 16 + 9 = 2.\nStep 3: For graph (ii), substitute the values: 7 - 14 + 9 = 2.\nStep 4: Since both graphs yield the value 2, Euler's formula holds for both.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Both graphs satisfy Euler's formula: v - e + f = 2.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant in town has an amazing selection of vegan options.\", \"The new restaurant in town serves the most amazing vegan quinoa bowls.\", \"463\", \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop down the street is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their famous caramel macchiato?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For what value of k is the line through the points (3, 2k+1) and (8, 4k-5) parallel to the x-axis?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: For a line to be parallel to the x-axis, its slope must be zero.\nStep 2: The slope between the points (3, 2k+1) and (8, 4k-5) is given by (4k-5 - (2k+1))/(8-3) = (2k-6)/5.\nStep 3: Set the numerator equal to zero: 2k-6 = 0, which simplifies to 2(k-3)=0.\nStep 4: Solve for k: k-3=0, so k=3.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new art museum is having a free admission day on Saturday. The hotel manager apologized for the inconvenience of the unexpected power outage during our stay, but promised a complimentary upgrade to a suite with an ocean view.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find all integers x, y, and z greater than or equal to 0 such that 2^x + 9 * 7^y = z^3.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice the equation: 2^x + 9 * 7^y = z^3, where x, y, z are nonnegative integers.\n2. Consider small values of y. For y = 1, the equation becomes 2^x + 9*7 = 2^x + 63 = z^3.\n3. The smallest cube that can be reached is 4^3 = 64. In that case, 2^x = 64 - 63 = 1, which implies x = 0 (since 2^0 = 1).\n4. Check: 2^0 + 9 * 7^1 = 1 + 63 = 64 = 4^3. Thus (x, y, z) = (0, 1, 4) is a solution.\n5. Testing other small values of y (e.g. y = 0 or y ≥ 2) does not yield any power of 2 that makes the difference a perfect cube. Therefore, no other solutions appear.\n6. Conclude that the unique solution in nonnegative integers is x = 0, y = 1, and z = 4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>(x, y, z) = (0, 1, 4)</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Have you tried that new Vietnamese restaurant downtown for lunch?\", \"The new coffee shop downtown is rumored to have the most extensive selection of tea flavors in the city.\", \"My favorite flavor of ice cream is rocky road.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In a single‐elimination tournament with 2^9 = 512 teams that have a strict ordering by skill (with the better team always winning), the teams are randomly arranged in the bracket. After all 511 matches are played, Joy is given the complete results and must produce a list of teams that is guaranteed to contain the third‐best team. What is the minimum possible length of Joy’s list?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In a single-elimination tournament with 512 teams, the champion wins 9 matches (since 2^9 = 512) and beats 9 different teams. 2. The only teams that can potentially be the second- or third-best are those that lost directly to one of the top two teams (the champion and the runner-up), because if a team never faced one of the top two, it must have lost to a team that is not among the very best, which is impossible given the strict ordering and the fact that the better team always wins. 3. The champion’s path provides 9 teams (its opponents) that could include the second-best or third-best team. 4. The runner-up also won 8 matches before facing the champion in the final (since the final match was against the champion), so the runner-up’s opponents number 8 (excluding the champion, who appears in both lists). 5. Therefore, the union of these two sets is 9 + 8 = 17 teams. No matter how the tournament is arranged, the third-best team must have been eliminated by either the champion or the runner-up, and so it must be among these 17 teams. 6. This shows that Joy can guarantee that the third-best team is in her list if she includes these 17 teams, and 17 is the smallest number that works in the worst-case seeding conditions.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>17</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I've been wanting to try that new vegan restaurant downtown for weeks, have you heard anything about it?\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has a lovely outdoor seating area with a great view of the park.\", \"I've been thinking about trying out that new vegan restaurant downtown for lunch tomorrow.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let π be a permutation of the numbers from 1 through 2012. What is the maximum possible number of integers n with 1 ≤ n ≤ 2011 for which π(n) divides π(n+1)?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We interpret the problem as follows. We are given a permutation π of the set {1,2,…,2012}. We wish to maximize the count of indices n (with 1 ≤ n ≤ 2011) for which the divisibility condition π(n) | π(n+1) holds. To maximize this count we want as many consecutive pairs as possible in our permutation sequence to satisfy the property. Equivalently, we want to arrange the 2012 numbers into as many long chains as possible, where in each chain every number divides its successor. When we eventually form one long permutation we have to join these chains by “connecting” them arbitrarily, and those connecting positions might not satisfy the divisibility condition. Thus, if we partition the set {1,2,…,2012} into k disjoint chains each of which is totally ordered by divisibility, then by ordering each chain in increasing order (which guarantees that each term divides the next), we obtain, within each chain of length L, L – 1 indices satisfying the condition. Connecting the chains arbitrarily gives a permutation in which the total number of indices that work is the sum of (L_i – 1) for each chain i. Since the sum of all L_i is 2012, the total count is 2012 – k. Thus, to maximize the number of indices, we wish to minimize k, the number of chains needed to cover S in a chain decomposition with respect to divisibility.\n\nA standard observation is that every positive integer can be uniquely expressed as 2^a · m where m is odd. Notice that if two numbers share the same odd part m then they are comparable (the one with the smaller power of 2 divides the one with the larger power of 2). Hence, for each fixed odd number m, the set of numbers of the form 2^a · m (that lie in {1,…,2012}) forms a chain. In a minimum chain decomposition we can take these chains indexed by the odd numbers that occur. The number of odd numbers between 1 and 2012 is exactly ⌈2012/2⌉ = 1006. Thus the minimum number of chains k required is 1006.\n\nThe maximum possible number of indices n for which π(n) divides π(n+1) is then 2012 − 1006 = 1006.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1006</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The weather in Paris is usually quite rainy in the spring.; Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their signature lattes this weekend?; The new coffee shop downtown is supposed to have an amazing avocado toast.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let H be the 4-dimensional unit hypercube with vertices (x, y, z, w) for each choice of x, y, z, w in {0, 1}. A bug starts at the vertex (0,0,0,0). In how many ways can the bug move to (1,1,1,1) by taking exactly 4 steps along the edges of H?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In a 4-dimensional hypercube, each edge corresponds to flipping one coordinate from 0 to 1 (or vice versa). The bug moves along one edge per step, flipping one coordinate at a time.\n2. To go from (0,0,0,0) to (1,1,1,1), every coordinate must flip exactly once (from 0 to 1). Hence, the bug must flip each of the 4 coordinates exactly one time, and the order in which these flips occur determines the path.\n3. The number of distinct orders in which the 4 coordinates can be flipped is 4! (i.e., 4 factorial).\n4. Calculate 4! = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>24</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant downtown has the best mac and cheese in the city.\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has the most delicious croissants I've ever tasted.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a set A with 10 elements, find the number of 2-configurations (i.e. ways to partition A into exactly 2 nonempty cells).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: A 2-configuration that partitions A into exactly 2 nonempty subsets is equivalent to partitioning a 10-element set into 2 blocks. \nStep 2: For partitions into 2 non-empty subsets, one can assign each element to one of two cells (2^10 possibilities) but must subtract the two cases where one cell is empty, i.e. 2^10 - 2. \nStep 3: Since the order of the cells is irrelevant, every partition is counted twice (each configuration appears in two orders), so divide by 2: ((2^10 - 2))/2. \nStep 4: Compute: 2^10 = 1024, then (1024 - 2) = 1022, and dividing by 2 gives 511.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>511</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new recipe for vegan chocolate cake has been a hit at my book club meetings. The new coffee shop downtown has the most adorable cat café upstairs.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>What fraction of the entire wall is painted red if the wall is divided into three equal sections, Matilda paints half of her section red, and Ellie paints one third of her section red?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Since the entire wall is divided into 3 equal parts, each section is 1/3 of the wall. 2. Matilda paints half of her section red, which is (1/2) * (1/3) = 1/6 of the wall. 3. Ellie paints one third of her section red, which is (1/3) * (1/3) = 1/9 of the wall. 4. The total painted red fraction is the sum of these two pieces: 1/6 + 1/9. 5. To add the fractions, find a common denominator: the least common denominator of 6 and 9 is 18. 6. Convert: 1/6 = 3/18 and 1/9 = 2/18. 7. Sum: 3/18 + 2/18 = 5/18.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>5/18</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences about the coffee shop, avocado toast, and the weather are irrelevant; the numbers 463, 878, and 876 do not contribute meaningfully to determining the structure's properties.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>How many edges does a square-based pyramid have?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that a square-based pyramid consists of a square base and four triangular faces meeting at a point (the apex). Step 2: The square base has 4 edges. Step 3: Each of the 4 lateral faces contributes one edge from the apex to a vertex of the base; there are 4 of these lateral edges. Step 4: In total, the pyramid has 4 (base edges) + 4 (lateral edges) = 8 edges.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>8</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant in town serves the best vegan quinoa bowls in the city.; The new employee seemed particularly fond of the office coffee machine.; The aroma of freshly brewed coffee filled the entire office, a welcome respite from the usual morning chaos.; \"463 x_0 identification number\" and the extraneous \"947\" in the set notation are irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of ordered 64-tuples (x₀, x₁, …, x₆₃) such that x₀, x₁, …, x₆₃ are distinct elements of the set {1, 2, …, 2017} and the weighted sum S = x₀ + x₁ + 2x₂ + 3x₃ + … + 63x₆₃ is divisible by 2017.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Total number of ordered 64-tuples with distinct elements chosen from {1,…,2017} is the permutation P(2017, 64) = 2017 × 2016 × … × (2017 − 63 + 1). \n2. We must count those tuples for which S = x₀ + x₁ + 2x₂ + 3x₃ + … + 63x₆₃ ≡ 0 (mod 2017). Notice that 2017 is a prime number and all the coefficients 1, 1, 2, 3, …, 63 (note that none of these coefficients is 0 modulo 2017, since 2017 > 63) are nonzero modulo 2017. \n3. This sum is a linear function in the variables x₀, …, x₆₃. When the xᵢ’s vary over all ordered selections of 64 distinct elements out of 2017, the weighted sum modulo 2017 is uniformly distributed among the 2017 residue classes. \n4. Therefore, exactly 1/2017 of all the P(2017, 64) tuples will have S ≡ 0 (mod 2017). \n5. The number of desired tuples is then P(2017, 64) / 2017. \n6. Since P(2017, 64) = 2017 × 2016 × … × (2017 − 63 + 1), dividing by 2017 cancels the first factor yielding 2016 × 2015 × … × (2017 − 63 + 1). This product is nothing but P(2016, 63).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>P(2016, 63)</answer>"
}

{
