  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Four points are chosen independently and uniformly at random from the interior of a regular dodecahedron. What is the probability that they form a tetrahedron whose interior contains the center of the dodecahedron?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that the problem asks for the probability that a randomly formed tetrahedron (from four uniformly chosen points in the interior of a convex body) contains a specific interior point (here, the center of a regular dodecahedron).\nStep 2: By symmetry and affine invariance, for any convex body in 3-dimensional space, the probability that the convex hull of 4 points (i.e., a tetrahedron) contains a fixed interior point is independent of the shape provided the body is convex. A well-known result tells us that if (n+1) points are chosen at random from a convex body in R^n, the probability that their convex hull contains a specified interior point is 1/(2^n).\nStep 3: For n = 3, this probability is 1/2^3 = 1/8.\nStep 4: Therefore, the probability that the tetrahedron formed by the 4 points contains the dodecahedron's center is 1/8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1/8</answer>"
}

{
