  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n > 1 be a positive integer. Ana and Bob play a game with n people arranged in a circle. Bob puts either a black or a white hat on each person’s head. Each person can see everyone else’s hat but not their own. Before Bob distributes the hats, Ana gives everyone a common strategy. Ana wants to maximize the number of correct individual guesses of hat colors, while Bob – after hearing the strategy – chooses the hat distribution adversarially to minimize the number of correct guesses. How many right guesses can Ana guarantee?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that this is a variant of the hat guessing game where a common strategy is fixed and an adversary (Bob) chooses the hat distribution after knowing the strategy. \nStep 2: A well‐known strategy uses parity. The players agree that one designated person (or a role played by one person in the cycle) will compute the parity (odd/even count) of, say, black hats observed. That person makes a guess that encodes this parity. The rest use the announced guess and the hats they see to deduce the color of their own hat.\nStep 3: In such strategies, regardless of Bob’s hat assignment, at most one guess might be forced to be wrong (the person who “sacrifices” his own guess to set the parity information). \nStep 4: Therefore, even if Bob chooses the worst-case hat distribution, the remaining n − 1 people can always correctly deduce their hat color. \nStep 5: Hence, the strategy guarantees that at least n − 1 people will guess correctly regardless of Bob’s distribution.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n - 1</answer>"
}

{
