  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n = 463 be a positive integer. Find the largest nonnegative real number f(n) with the following property: For any real numbers a₁, a₂, …, aₙ whose sum is an integer, there exists some index i such that |aᵢ - 1/2| ≥ f(n).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Understand that we need the maximum f(n) such that in every n-tuple (a₁, a₂, …, aₙ) with a₁ + … + aₙ an integer, at least one aᵢ deviates from 1/2 by at least f(n).\nStep 2: The worst-case scenario is when all aᵢ are as close as possible to 1/2. In order to force the total sum to be an integer, if we try to have each aᵢ equal to 1/2 + δ, then the sum becomes n/2 + nδ and must be an integer.\nStep 3: When n is odd, n/2 is a half-integer. Therefore, in order for n/2 + nδ to be an integer, nδ must be a half-integer. The smallest nonzero absolute possibility for nδ is 1/2, which gives |δ| = 1/(2n).\nStep 4: If all aᵢ equal 1/2 + 1/(2n), then every |aᵢ - 1/2| equals 1/(2n) and the sum is an integer. Thus, one cannot require a larger f(n) (otherwise the counterexample would violate the property). Also, for even n, the trivial example aᵢ = 1/2 for all i would yield a sum that is an integer and zero deviation, forcing f(n) = 0. \nStep 5: Since n = 463 is odd, the largest possible f(n) that works is f(463) = 1/(2×463) = 1/926.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1/926</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Each flight has a 574 fixed price which is the occupy ; same in both directions.\"; \"The new restaurant downtown has an amazing vegan menu.\"; \"The new artisanal coffee shop in town has a lovely patio area perfect for meeting friends on a sunny afternoon.\"; \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a loyalty program to its frequent customers?\"; \"Anna always takes the 876 cheapest flight from her current city to some city 878 she, go has n't visited yet.\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An airline operates flights between every pair of capital cities in the European Union. For any given city, the prices of flights to the other cities are pairwise distinct and the price is the same in both directions. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once (they may start in different cities). At each step, Anna always takes the cheapest flight available from her current city to a city that she has not yet visited, while Bella always takes the most expensive available flight. Is it true that Bella’s tour will always cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: The problem involves a complete graph on the set of capital cities, where from each city the flights to all other cities have distinct prices and are symmetric. Thus, for every city, one can order the available outbound flights from cheapest to most expensive.\nStep 2: In forming a tour that visits every city exactly once, each city (except the last one in the tour) contributes one flight from that city. Anna’s rule guarantees that at each city she picks the cheapest available flight among those connecting to unvisited cities, while Bella picks the most expensive one.\nStep 3: For each city, since the set of related flight prices is fixed and ordered, the flight chosen by Bella from a city (if she leaves from that city) is at least as expensive as the flight chosen by Anna from that city. Note that even though the order in which the cities are visited might vary between the two tours, the local decision at each city results in Bella incurring a cost that is at least as high as Anna’s for that departure.\nStep 4: Consequently, the overall cost of Bella’s tour — the sum of the most expensive choices at each step — must be at least as large as the overall cost of Anna’s tour, which is the sum of the cheapest choices at the corresponding steps.\nStep 5: Therefore, it is indeed true that Bella’s tour will always cost at least as much as Anna’s tour.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, Bella's tour will always cost at least as much as Anna's tour.</answer>"
}

