  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the largest integer less than 2012 such that every one of its divisors has at most two 1's in its binary representation.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that a number whose binary representation has at most two 1's must be of one of the two forms: a power of 2 (i.e. 2^a) or the sum of two distinct powers of 2 (i.e. 2^a + 2^b with a > b). Since any divisor d of n must satisfy the condition and n itself is a divisor, n must be one of these numbers.\n2. For a number n = 2^a, all its divisors are powers of 2 (i.e. of the form 2^k) and these obviously have only one 1 in binary. However, the largest power of 2 less than 2012 is 1024 (2^10), which might not be as large as some numbers of the second form.\n3. Next consider numbers of the form n = 2^a + 2^b. Their binary representation contains exactly two 1's. We wish to find the maximum such n that is < 2012.\n4. The largest powers of 2 below 2012 are 1024 (2^10) and 512 (2^9). Their sum is 1024 + 512 = 1536, which is less than 2012. Any other choice with smaller exponents will yield a smaller number.\n5. It remains to check that every divisor of 1536 has at most two 1's in its binary representation. Notice that 1536 = 1024 + 512 can be factored as 1536 = 2^9 × 3 (since 2^9 = 512 and 512×3 = 1536). Its divisors are of the form 2^k and 3×2^k for appropriate k. The number 3 in binary is 11 (two 1's) and multiplying by a power of 2 only shifts the bits (i.e. appends zeros on the right) and does not change the number of 1's. Hence every divisor of 1536 meets the condition.\n6. Therefore, 1536 is the largest integer less than 2012 for which every divisor has at most two 1's in its binary representation.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1536</answer>"
}

