  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>You have five different pairs of socks (a total of 10 socks). Each day for five days you pick two socks at random without replacement to wear. What is the probability that on the third day and on the fifth day you end up wearing a matching pair (i.e. the two socks come from the same pair)?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: On any given day, you select 2 socks out of 10 socks. Once you pick the first sock, there is exactly 1 sock among the remaining 9 that constitutes its matching pair. Thus, the probability of drawing a matching pair on a single day is 1/9.\nStep 2: The events on different days (day 3 and day 5) are independent. Therefore, the probability of both events occurring (a match on day 3 and a match on day 5) is the product of their individual probabilities: (1/9) * (1/9) = 1/81.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1/81</answer>"
}

