  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let A₀A₁A₂...A₉ be the vertices of a regular decagon. Compute ∠A₀A₃A₇ (with vertex A₃) in degrees.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In a regular decagon, the central angle between consecutive vertices is 360° / 10 = 36°.\n2. The inscribed angle ∠A₀A₃A₇ is formed at vertex A₃ by the chords A₃A₀ and A₃A₇. Its intercepted arc is the arc from A₀ to A₇ that does not include A₃.\n3. Labeling the vertices in order (A₀, A₁, ..., A₉), the intercepted arc is the shorter arc connecting A₀ to A₇. The difference between the indices is 7, but since the circle is cyclical, the smaller difference is 10 - 7 = 3. Thus, the intercepted arc spans 3 consecutive sides.\n4. The measure of this intercepted arc is 3 × 36° = 108°.\n5. An inscribed angle is half the measure of its intercepted arc, so ∠A₀A₃A₇ = 108° / 2 = 54°.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>54°</answer>"
}

