  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant down the street has an amazing selection of vegan options.\", \"I'm looking forward to trying that new restaurant downtown this weekend.\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of gluten-free pastries.\", \"is Joseph Black black.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An urn contains 463 white balls and an unspecified number of black balls, with at least two balls of each color present. Two balls are drawn from the urn without replacement. Find the probability (expressed in percent) that the first ball drawn is white and the second ball drawn is black.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let the number of white balls be W = 463 and let the number of black balls be B (with B ≥ 2). The total number of balls is T = 463 + B.\\n2. The probability that the first ball drawn is white is P(white first) = 463/(463 + B).\\n3. After one white ball is removed, there remain 462 white balls and B black balls, so the new total is (462 + B). The probability that the second ball drawn is black then is P(black second | white first) = B/(462 + B).\\n4. The overall probability is the product of the two probabilities: P = (463/(463 + B)) × (B/(462 + B)).\\n5. To convert this probability into a percentage, multiply by 100. Thus, the probability in percent is: Percentage = (463 × B / ((463 + B)(462 + B))) × 100.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>(463 × B)/((463+B)(462+B)) × 100, where B is the number of black balls (with B ≥ 2)</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of flavored lattes., I'm really looking forward to trying the new coffee shop that just opened up down the street., The new avant-garde art exhibition in town is really making a statement with its use of recycled materials.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For each positive integer n, let s(n) be the sum of the squares of the digits of n. For example, s(15)=1^2+5^2=26. Determine all integers n ≥ 1 such that s(n) = n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that for any positive integer n with d digits, the maximum possible value of s(n) is 81d (since each digit is at most 9 and 9^2=81). For d ≥ 2, n is at least 10 and grows roughly exponentially, so it is unlikely that s(n) can catch up with n. Thus, we begin by considering the one‐digit numbers.\nStep 2: For a one-digit integer n (i.e. n from 1 to 9), s(n) = n^2. We need n^2 = n, which leads to n(n − 1) = 0. Since n ≥ 1, the only solution is n = 1.\nStep 3: For numbers with more than one digit, note that n is at least 10, but the maximum possible s(n) for 2 digits is 81×2 = 162 and for 3 digits is 81×3 = 243. In each case, for most numbers n, s(n) is much less than n. A quick check or logical reasoning shows that no multi-digit number can satisfy s(n) = n.\nStep 4: Therefore, the only solution is n = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I'm craving a cup of coffee to start my day.\", \"I've been meaning to ask you, have you tried that new coffee shop downtown?\", \"I just realized I forgot to water my plants last weekend, now they're starting to wilt.\", \"463\", \"succeeding\", \"pick up\", \"947\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Sherry is waiting for a train. Every minute, there is a 75% chance that a train will arrive. However, because she is engrossed in her game of sudoku, even if a train arrives, she has a 75% chance of not noticing it. What is the probability that Sherry catches the train in the next five minutes?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In each minute, the probability a train arrives is 75% (or 0.75). If a train arrives, the probability that Sherry notices it (and hence catches it) is 25% (since she has a 75% chance of not noticing). Therefore, the effective probability of catching the train in any given minute is 0.75 * 0.25 = 0.1875 (or 18.75%).\\n2. The probability that she does not catch a train in one minute is 1 - 0.1875 = 0.8125.\\n3. Over five independent minutes, the probability that she misses catching a train every minute is (0.8125)^5.\\n4. The probability that she catches the train at least once in five minutes is 1 - (0.8125)^5.\\n5. Calculating (0.8125)^5 exactly, note that 0.8125 = 13/16 so (13/16)^5 = (13^5)/(16^5) = 371293/1048576 ≈ 0.354.\\n6. Thus, the final probability, 1 - 0.354, is approximately 0.646 or 64.6%.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Approximately 64.6%</answer>"
}

