  "solution_steps": "1. Observe that each entry of the matrix A is given by i+j. This can be written as the sum of two terms: one depending solely on i and the other solely on j. \n2. Define the column vector u = [1, 2, ..., n]^T and let 1 denote the n-dimensional vector of all ones. Then we can express A = u*1^T + 1*u^T. \n3. Each of the matrices u*1^T and 1*u^T has rank 1 (provided n ≥ 1). \n4. The sum of two rank-1 matrices has rank at most 2, and since u and 1 are linearly independent when n ≥ 2, the rank of A is exactly 2.\n5. In the special case when n = 1, the matrix is 1×1 and its rank is 1. However, for a typical n×n matrix with n ≥ 2, the answer is 2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2 (for n ≥ 2)</answer>"
