  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let f: Q → Q be a function such that for any x, y ∈ Q, the number f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) is an integer. Decide whether it follows that there exists a constant c such that f(x) - cx is an integer for every rational number x.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. The given condition states that for all x, y ∈ Q, f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) is an integer. This means that f is “almost” additive—it is additive up to an integer error term.\n2. Consider choosing c = f(1). For any rational number x, one can build x (when x is an integer) using the additivity condition. By induction and using the property repeatedly, one shows that f(n) - n·f(1) is an integer for every integer n. For negative integers a similar argument holds by considering additive inverses.\n3. For a general rational number x = p/q (with p, q ∈ Z, q ≠ 0), one notes that q·f(p/q) and f(p) are connected by the near-additivity property. In effect, one can show that q·f(p/q) differs from p·f(1) by an integer, hence f(p/q) - (p/q)·f(1) is an integer divided by q. However, since the property must hold exactly as an integer for any choice of x in Q and the error term from splitting any rational can be absorbed into a suitable integer, a careful analysis (using the fact that Q is divisible) establishes that one may always choose c = f(1) so that f(x) - c·x ∈ Z for all x ∈ Q.\n4. Thus, the answer is yes: there exists such a constant c, and one natural choice is c = f(1).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, such a constant exists and one may take c = f(1).</answer>"
